Erläuterungen zur globalen Wettbewerbsfähigkeit
Im November hat das Weltwirtschaftsforum und das Zentrum für Internationale Entwicklung der Harvard-Universität den Global Competitiveness Report (Wettbewerbsfähigkeitsbericht) für das Jahr 2001 veröffentlicht.
In der 75 Länder umfassenden Studie belegen Finnland, die Vereinigten Staaten und Kanada die Plätze eins bis drei, während Nicaragua, Nigeria und Simbabwe die Schlusslichter bilden.
(Alle Ranglisten sind unter www.weforum.com ) nachzulesen.)
Als mitverantwortlicher Leiter dieser jährlichen Studie werde ich oft gefragt, was Wettbewerbsfähigkeit überhaupt bedeutet.
Is there also an economic competition among countries besides military ones?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is defined very precisely: namely as a country's ability to achieve sustainable economic growth over a medium-term period – i.e., a period of five years.
This definition, however, does not mean that the competitiveness of one country simultaneously indicates a lack of competitiveness in another country.
All countries on Earth could achieve higher growth rates with better political strategies at the same time.
Nevertheless, it is sensible to create a ranking of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Every country is interested in knowing whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep up with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In some ways, economic growth can be compared to a sporting competition where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries, for example, compete for internationally mobile capital.
The more capital a country can attract through foreign direct investment, the less capital another country receives.
Vollkommen klar wird dies, wenn sich Länder um ein bestimmtes Investitionsprojekt bewerben.
Wenn Intel ein neues Halbleiterwerk plant, werden verschiedene Länder eingeladen, Angebote zu unterbreiten.
Der Wettbewerb um den Zuschlag ist hart und vielfach wird auch mit Steuerbegünstigungen, Infrastrukturverbesserungen und sogar mit Studienplananpassungen an der örtlichen technischen Universität geworben.
In diesem Jahr ermittelten wir die Wettbewerbsfähigkeit (Wachstumsfähigkeit) eines Landes anhand dreier weitgefasster Kriterien: (1) Technologie, (2) öffentliche Institutionen und (3) makroökonomische Stabilität.
Für jede dieser Kategorien ermittelten wir Kennzahlen, deren Durchschnittswerte nach einer speziellen Methode berechnet wurden, um dann einen allgemeinen Wachstums- und Wettbewerbsindex zu erstellen.
The criterion Technology refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and utilize technologies developed elsewhere.
Some countries like the USA, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development and thus achieve high values in innovation.
Other countries like Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and therefore achieve little in terms of new products and processes.
Innovation-friendly countries also enjoy a high level of prosperity due to these innovations.
In this area, the USA, Canada, and Finland occupy the top three positions in the ranking.
The criterion „public institutions” refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts impartial and independent?
Can one trust that the government fulfills its obligations according to the law?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and ineffective judges.
High ethical standards enhance economic performance.
In this regard, the Nordic countries are globally leading, and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also at the top of the rankings.
Cronyism is virtually unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced government budget, a realistic exchange rate of the national currency, the ability of companies and the government to get loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will fulfill its financial obligations.
As an example, we learned from Asia in the late 1990s that a macroeconomic crisis can destroy growth, even if the companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries regarding macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: innovation-oriented and non-innovation-oriented.
Only about 20 countries actively engage in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the wealthiest in the world, a system of technological innovation of high quality is considered a prerequisite for sustained competitiveness.
The universities must be excellent, state laboratories should be of world-class standard, and government and industry should make strong investments in research and development.
An important factor for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher education and universities after compulsory schooling.
In the United States and Canada, this proportion is 80%.
For the "non-innovation-oriented" countries, technology is equally important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed within the country itself.
Some countries specialize in importing new technologies, while others do so to a lesser extent.
In the past ten or fifteen years, a large part of technology imports occurred through foreign direct investment.
American firms that invested heavily in Mexico or Taiwanese firms that invested in mainland China brought new technologies with them that increased the efficiency of production in the respective target economy.
Therefore, it was certainly worthwhile for the respective countries to vie vigorously for these foreign investments: They bring not only capital but also new technologies.
A strength and weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is oriented towards the medium term and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suitable for evaluating short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore ironic that many of the countries that placed first this year, such as the USA or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while other less ranked countries like China (ranked 39) are not affected by the global recession.
<s>Partially, the slowing of the economy is linked to the September 11 attacks, but it is increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it via trade and production networks were already slipping into recession before September.
<s>Nevertheless, we believe that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the US will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth over the next five years.
